Free trade enthusiasts
Cambridge – I was invited to guest lecture in a globalization course at Harvard recently. "I must warn you,"
one of them told me beforehand, "these students are strong proponents of globalization."
He had asked the students in the first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, and over 90% favored the former.
And this was before he started teaching about the magic effects of comparative advantage.
We know that asking the same questions of a representative sample — rather than Harvard students — in a real survey would yield a very different result.
In the US, the ratio of opponents to supporters of trade restrictions is 2:1.
But the answers from Harvard students are not particularly surprising.
Because people with higher technical skills and better education tend to be more supportive of free trade than blue-collar workers.
And perhaps these Harvard students had already anticipated their own (future) paths and made their decisions accordingly.
Or perhaps they simply do not understand how trade works.
After all, when I met them, I deliberately asked the same question in a different form, emphasizing the distributional effects that trade might generate.
The consensus in favor of fair trade disappeared even faster than I had anticipated.
To start off, I asked everyone whether they agreed to participate in a particularly magical experiment.
I chose Nicholas and John as volunteers, then told them that I had a way to make $200 disappear from Nicholas’s account – poof! – while adding $300 to John’s, and that this social engineering feat could add an extra $100 in value to the entire class.
Will they allow me to play this little trick?
The result was that only a small portion firmly agreed, many were hesitant, and even more opposed implementing this change.

Clearly, students find it difficult to tolerate such a significant income redistribution, even when the overall economic pie has grown.
I then asked why, despite this, most of them instinctively supported free trade, which also leads to a similar – indeed, even greater – wealth redistribution from losers to winners.
The students seemed stunned.
I continued by saying, let's assume that Nicholas and John both started competing small companies.
John worked harder, saved more, invested more, and produced a better product, so not only did he end up $300 richer than Nicholas, but he also drove his competitor out of the market and cost him $200.
How many students approved of this outcome?
This time, most voted in favor – in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I then proposed another hypothesis directly related to international trade.
If John drove Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or by outsourcing business processes to China, where labor rights are not yet well established?
Or by employing child labor in Indonesia?
This time, the degree of approval for the shift decreases with each of these options.
In addition, technological innovation, like trade, can make certain people more vulnerable. What is your stance on this?
Only a few students were willing to curb the development of technology.
To almost everyone, banning the production of light bulbs to save candlemakers' jobs is a foolish idea.
Therefore, what students oppose is not redistribution per se, but specific forms of it.
Like most of us, they are concerned about the fairness of the process.
To judge the outcomes of redistribution, we must know the objective context in which they arise.
We do not resent Bill Gates or Warren Buffett's vast fortunes, even if their competitors have had tough times, perhaps because they and their competitors operate under similar basic rules and face very similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett had amassed their wealth through fraud, violating labor laws, damaging the environment, or exploiting subsidies from foreign governments, our views would be quite different.
If we cannot tolerate redistribution achieved by violating widely accepted moral norms at home, how can we justify it when it involves international transactions?
Similarly, when we expect that the effects of redistribution will lead to equality over the long term, and that everyone will ultimately benefit, we are likely to be less concerned about income transfers.
This is why we still believe in promoting technological development, even though it may bring short-term negative impacts on certain individuals.
On the other hand, when trade continuously hits the same group of people – low-skilled blue-collar workers – we become concerned about globalization.
But many economists ignore these obvious differences.
They tend to attribute concerns about globalization to foolish and selfish protectionist motives or ignorance, without realizing that the most crucial issue is actually one of morality.
Because they fail to recognize that international trade sometimes – though not often – can lead to redistributions of wealth that we cannot accept domestically, these economists are unable to properly engage in public discourse.
And if their moral arguments are so weak, how can they defend trade vigorously?
When globalization occasionally raises a thorny issue related to the legitimation of redistribution effects, we should not reflexively respond with trade restrictions.
There are many pros and cons to weigh, including the possibility that globalization may deprive people elsewhere of wealth to an even greater extent than it does Americans.
But democratic countries should have a more appropriate discussion about this and make conscious and more considered decisions.
The obsession with globalization simply because it enlarges the pie will inevitably erode its legitimacy over the long term.
